rve as an introduction to them, but, by giving complete references to the published literature, the authors have made the work useful to a reader who does not know all the aspects of the theory of automorphic forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAutomorphic forms. 0aRepresentations of groups. 0aTrace formulas. 7aMATHEMATICS / Group Theory.2bisacsh  a0E.  aAddition.  aAdmissible representation.  aAlgebraic group.  aAlgebraic number field.  aApproximation.  aArchimedean property.  aAutomorphic form.  aAutomorphism.  aBase change.  aBig O notation.  aBinomial coefficient.  aCanonical map.  aCartan subalgebra.  aCartan subgroup.  aCentral simple algebra.  aCharacteristic polynomial.  aClosure (mathematics).  aCombination.  aComputation.  aConjecture.  aConjugacy class.  aConnected component (graph theory).  aContinuous function.  aContradiction.  aCorollary.  aCounting.  aCoxeter element.  aCusp form.  aCyclic permutation.  aDense set.  aDensity theorem.  aDeterminant.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDiscrete series representation.  aDiscrete spectrum.  aDivision algebra.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aEisenstein series.  aExact sequence.  aExistential quantification.  aField extension.  aFinite group.  aFinite set.  aFourier transform.  aFunctor.  aFundamental lemma (Langlands program).  aGalois extension.  aGalois group.  aGlobal field.  aGrothendieck group.  aGroup representation.  aHaar measure.  aHarmonic analysis.  aHecke algebra.  aHilbert's Theorem 90.  aIdentity component.  aInduced representation.  aInfinite product.  aInfinitesimal character.  aInvariant measure.  aIrreducibility (mathematics).  aIrreducible representation.  aL-function.  aLanglands classification.  aLaure